{"parentUuid":"2dbe45d9-22b3-46ac-94f7-3362b0fb40ba","isSidechain":false,"message":{"id":"bee7bb7e-b553-47ca-ad21-f3a81b8a3e79","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"deepseek-v4-pro","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, now I have a clearer picture:\n\n1. `D:\\桌面` exists with 127 items (mostly folders)\n2. The folder attribute is `ReadOnly, Directory`\n3. Both registry locations point Desktop to `D:\\桌面`\n\nThe problem is most likely that the folder has the `ReadOnly` attribute set on it, and/or that the `desktop.ini` file is missing or has issues. When Windows moves the Desktop folder, it should set specific attributes and create a `desktop.ini` file.\n\nBut wait - the ReadOnly flag on a folder in Windows is actually normal and typically ignored by Windows for folders. The real issue might be something else.\n\nLet me think about what else could cause File Explorer to hang with a green progress bar:\n\n1. **Shell extension conflicts** - Some shell extension might be hanging when trying to process files in the new Desktop location\n2. **Thumbnail generation** - If there are media files, Explorer might be trying to generate thumbnails\n3. **Search indexing** - Windows Search might be trying to index the new location\n4. **desktop.ini issues** - Missing or corrupted desktop.ini\n5. **Permission issues** - The folder might not have proper permissions\n6. **The ReadOnly attribute** - Though normally ignored, sometimes it causes issues\n\nThe most common fix for this issue is:\n1. Reset the Desktop folder back to default location\n2. Restart Explorer\n3. Or fix the desktop.ini\n\nLet me check if desktop.ini exists and also check the folder's read-only status more carefully. Also, let me check if there's a `desktop.ini` file.","signature":"bee7bb7e-b553-47ca-ad21-f3a81b8a3e79"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":297,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":32256,"output_tokens":516,"server_tool_use":{"we