{"parentUuid":"399cb040-82c5-4719-a33f-eba237a2aeb9","isSidechain":false,"message":{"id":"b2a730cf-d90b-4c8a-b8e6-65217820c5a5","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"deepseek-v4-pro","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, all three drives are DriveType 3 (fixed local disk), no CD/DVD drives or network drives. No optical drive issue.\n\nSo the drives are all fine:\n- C: 107GB, 20GB free\n- D: 196GB, 156GB free (Volume: 软件)\n- E: 196GB, 78GB free (Volume: 文档)\n\nNo network drives, no CD/DVD drives.\n\nSo the problem is NOT a drive enumeration issue (at least not from missing media or disconnected network drives).\n\nNow let me focus on what I found:\n1. Desktop → D:\\桌面\n2. Downloads (`{374DE290}`) → D:\\桌面 (SAME path!)\n3. `{7D83EE9B}` → D:\\桌面\n4. `{754AC886}` → D:\\桌面\n\nThis means multiple known folders are pointing to the same `D:\\桌面` path. Downloads going to the same folder as Desktop is very unusual and could be causing the conflict.\n\nLet me verify what `{7D83EE9B-2244-4E70-B1F5-5393042AF1E4}` actually is. Let me look it up in the KnownFolders registry.\n\nThis could be the root cause. When Explorer tries to resolve these known folders, having multiple GUIDs pointing to the same path may cause a deadlock or infinite loop in the shell namespace.\n\nActually, let me check what these GUIDs map to by looking at the KnownFolders registry key.","signature":"b2a730cf-d90b-4c8a-b8e6-65217820c5a5"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":255,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":48000,"output_tokens":554,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"stop_details":null},"type":"assistant","uuid":"307fb7df-b639-480b-ab73-1a664670b9e4","timestamp":"2026-05-18T03:00:44.255Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cw