{"parentUuid":"8a10e481-7971-48e3-9fc4-f2b91b1ae3a7","isSidechain":false,"message":{"id":"78ecf884-bf12-4453-bd4b-6f97cd1bb59f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"deepseek-v4-pro","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still the same issue. The Downloads fix didn't resolve it. Let me think about what else could be causing the \"This PC\" green progress bar to hang.\n\nLet me reconsider the problem. The user says \"打开此电脑\" and the address bar shows a green progress bar that fills up but gets stuck, and nothing displays below. This is the \"This PC\" view specifically.\n\nLet me think about what Explorer does when opening \"This PC\":\n1. It enumerates all drives (C:, D:, E:) and shows their icons, labels, free space\n2. It also shows the \"Folders\" section which includes Desktop, Documents, Downloads, Music, Pictures, Videos\n3. It shows \"Devices and drives\" section\n\nThe \"Folders\" section in \"This PC\" shows the user's shell folders as shortcuts. If any of these folders can't be resolved or accessed, Explorer might hang.\n\nBut we already fixed the Downloads conflict. What else could be wrong?\n\nLet me think about what other registry entries might be problematic:\n1. `{754AC886-DF64-4CBA-86B5-F7FBF4FBCEF5}` = \"ThisPCDesktopFolder\" → D:\\桌面 - this was in both Shell Folders and User Shell Folders. Is ThisPCDesktopFolder supposed to point to a different location?\n\nActually, wait. Let me look at this more carefully. In the Shell Folders key, `{754AC886}` was shown as \"ThisPCDesktopFolder\". This is NOT a standard known folder GUID that should be in the user's Shell Folders. It might be a leftover or incorrectly added entry.\n\nWait, actually, let me re-read the Shell Folders output. I saw:\n- `{374DE290-123F-4565-9164-39C4925E467B}: D:\\桌面` (Downloads) - this was in Shell Folders\n- `{754AC886-DF64-4CBA-86B5-F7FBF4FBCEF5}: D:\\桌面` (ThisPCDesktopFolder) - this was in Shell Folders\n\nActually, `{754AC886-DF64-4CBA-86B5-F7FBF4FBCEF5}` - let me check what this is. Looking it up...\n\nActually, this GUID might be `FOLDERID_Desktop` in some context. Let me look at standard known folders:\n- `B4BFCC3A-DB2C-424C-B029-7FE99A87C641` = FOLDERID_Desktop (the main one)\n- `754AC886-DF64-4CBA-86B5-F7FBF4FBCEF5` = ??? \n\nHmm, I need to verify this. Let me search the registry for what `754AC886-DF64-4CBA-86B5-F7FBF4FBCEF5` actually maps to.\n\nBut wait, the Name I got earlier was \"ThisPCDesktopFolder\". This is suspicious - it sounds like an internal name for the Desktop shown in \"This PC\" view. If this is pointing to the user's Desktop path, it might be correct. But the fact that it's separately registered in Shell Folders could be causing issues.\n\nOK let me take a step back. The fact that cache clearing + Explorer restart + Downloads fix didn't work suggests the problem might be something else entirely. Let me consider:\n\n1. **Shell extension** - A third-party shell extension is hanging when Explorer tries to enumerate \"This PC\"\n2. **Namespace conflict** - Something in the CLSID namespace under \"This PC\" is broken\n3. **Drive properties** - Explorer can't read properties from one of the drives\n4. **Specific to the user's machine** - Something applications installed\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. Let me check:\n1. If Explorer can open specific folders (like D:\\ directly) vs. \"This PC\"\n2. Check shell extensions that hook into \"This PC\"\n3. Check the namespace under CLSID for \"This PC\"\n\nActually, a very common cause for the \"This PC\" green bar is a specific shell extension for drive context menus or property sheets. Let me use ShellExView approach or check the registry.\n\nBut actually, since I can't easily identify the specific shell extension, let me try another approach:\n\n1. Rebuild the icon cache properly (with Explorer stopped)\n2. Clear the thumbnail cache again\n3. Try to reset the \"This PC\" folder template\n\nOR, let me try the nuclear option for \"This PC\": reset its