{"parentUuid":"dc01badc-d48d-478c-9651-087e5d530c10","isSidechain":false,"message":{"id":"7fb7d416-66f8-4a7c-a4fb-f88247072510","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"deepseek-v4-pro","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The encoding problems are really bad. All Chinese characters are getting garbled both in input and output. Let me take a completely different approach.\n\nInstead of trying to use Chinese paths in the command line, let me:\n1. Write a PowerShell script file (using the Write tool which should handle UTF-8 properly)\n2. Execute it with `powershell -File`\n\nBut the previous script file also had encoding issues (Get-Item couldn't find D:\\下载 even though it exists).\n\nLet me try a different approach: use the Write tool to create the desktop.ini file directly at D:\\下载, and also use a script that avoids Chinese characters in paths by using wildcards or .NET methods.\n\nActually wait - the Write tool should be able to write files with Chinese paths correctly. The issue is only with the bash shell handling Chinese characters.\n\nLet me write the desktop.ini file directly. A standard desktop.ini for Downloads folder should contain:\n\n```\n[.ShellClassInfo]\nLocalizedResourceName=@%SystemRoot%\\system32\\shell32.dll,-21798\nIconResource=%SystemRoot%\\system32\\imageres.dll,-184\n```\n\nFor the Desktop folder, it's:\n```\n[.ShellClassInfo]\nLocalizedResourceName=@%SystemRoot%\\system32\\shell32.dll,-21769\nIconResource=%SystemRoot%\\system32\\imageres.dll,-183\n```\n\nAnd for the Downloads folder, it should be:\n- LocalizedResourceName: @%SystemRoot%\\system32\\shell32.dll,-21798 (this is the string resource for \"Downloads\" in Chinese Windows)\n- IconResource: %SystemRoot%\\system32\\imageres.dll,-184\n\nWait, I need to check the correct resource IDs. Let me verify:\n- Desktop localized name: shell32.dll,-21769 → \"Desktop\" → in Chinese: \"桌面\"\n- Downloads localized name: shell32.dll,-21798 → \"Downloads\" → in Chinese: \"下载\"\n\nActually, the resource IDs might differ between Windows versions. But the standard ones should work.\n\nLet me write the desktop.ini to D:\\下载. But first, I need to figure out the encoding issue with the Write tool. The Write tool should handle file paths correctly.\n\nActually, let me just write the desktop.ini using the Write tool directly.\n\nBut wait - there's also the issue that the Downloads folder's name is garbled. The garbled name \"涓嫡浇\" in Explorer is because:\n1. There's no desktop.ini, so Windows falls back to the folder name\n2. But the folder name IS \"下载\", so it should show correctly...\n\nUnless... the desktop.ini from a DIFFERENT folder is being picked up, or the Known Folder registration has a corrupted display name.\n\nActually, \"涓嫡浇\" - let me decode this more carefully. If I take \"涓嫡浇\" and convert it from UTF-8 bytes to GBK or vice versa...\n\nActually, for now let me focus on what I can fix:\n1. Create desktop.ini for D:\\下载\n2. Also check if D:\\桌面\\desktop.ini is intact\n3. Try to fix the \"This PC\" green bar issue\n\nThe green bar might be caused by Explorer trying to resolve the Downloads folder's display name, finding no desktop.ini, and then getting stuck in the Known Folder resolution.\n\nLet me write both desktop.ini files and see if that fixes the issue.\n\nActually, I just realized: the D:\\下载 folder was probably just created by us earlier when we set the registry. If it already existed (which it did), it might not have had a proper desktop.ini.\n\nLet me create the desktop.ini for D:\\下载. The Write tool should handle this.\n\nActually, I should also check: when the user says \"左侧的下载变成了：涓嫡浇\" - this is the Explorer navigation pane on the left side. This suggests Explorer IS working partially (it shows the navigation pane), but the main content area (where \"This PC\" drives should be) is not loading.\n\nHmm, but the user originally said \"一直显示正在处理\" - so Explorer might be partially responsive but stuck on loading content.\n\nLet me focus on